}{}${C}_{43}^2$\end{document}=903 (SALD) component pairs (Vergara et al. 2019). A penalty on the L1 norm was imposed in the graphic LASSO framework with 100 repetitions to promote sparsity in estimation (Friedman et al. 2008). We selected a 56 s segmented window length based on previous work indicating that window lengths between 30 and 60 s successfully capture resting-state dFC fluctuations and do not yield substantially different results, which, moreover, allowed us to match the window length of the LEMON dataset to the SALD dataset (Preti et al. 2017). To our knowledge, no gold standard exists for window length in dFC analyses. To nevertheless ascertain that our results were robust to variations in window length, we repeated our analyses of dFC states using two additional commonly-used window lengths (30–40s: Lemon: 25TR * 1.4 = 35 s, SALD: 17TR * 2 = 34 s; 40–50s: Lemon: 35TR * 1.4 = 49 s, SALD: 22TR * 2 = 44 s, see Temporal properties section). Sex was included as a covariate in the estimation. Finally, all resulting FC matrices were transformed to z-scores using Fisher’s z-transformation.
